text: Tick-borne relapsing fever is a type of disease that can be transmitted by soft ticks, such as the Ornithodoros parkeri and Ornithodoros hermsii. It is characterized by recurring or relapsing episodes of fever, and can cause symptoms such as tachypnea, tachycardia, hepatosplenomegaly, lymphadenopathy, and enlarged spleen. It is caused by the bacteria Borrelia hermsii, Borrelia parkeri or Borrelia duttoni.

text: Persistent fetal circulation syndrome is a type of pulmonary hypertension that occurs due to abnormal blood flow in the lungs. It is also known by other names such as persistent foetal circulation, congenital alveolar capillary dysplasia with misalignment of pulmonary veins, and persistent fetal circulation syndrome. This condition affects newborn infants and can lead to serious complications if left untreated. It is important for healthcare professionals to monitor and manage this condition properly in order to prevent long-term damage to the lungs and other organs.

Sphenoidal sinusitis is a type of sinusitis that affects the sphenoid sinuses. Sphenoidal sinusitis can be classified as acute or chronic, with acute sphenoidal sinusitis lasting for less than 4 weeks and chronic sphenoidal sinusitis lasting for more than 12 weeks. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have sinusitis, as it can lead to complications such as orbital cellulitis or abscesses if left untreated. Treatment options for sphenoidal sinusitis may include antibiotics, nasal corticosteroid sprays, and sinus irrigation, among other measures.

Corpus luteum cysts are a type of ovarian cyst that form as a result of the accumulation of fluid in the follicle after an egg has been released. These cysts are usually harmless and cause few, if any symptoms. However, they can be large enough to cause discomfort or pain, particularly during the menstrual cycle. If you have a corpus luteum cyst, it is important to follow your healthcare provider's recommendations for treatment, which may include monitoring the cyst with ultrasound or surgical removal if necessary.

Traumatic glaucoma is a type of glaucoma that occurs as a result of ocular trauma. This can lead to elevated intraocular pressure, which causes damage to the optic nerve and results in progressive vision loss. Symptoms of traumatic glaucoma may include progressive decreased vision, visual field defects, and decreased peripheral vision. It is important to seek medical attention if you have experienced ocular trauma to determine if you have developed traumatic glaucoma.

Renal osteodystrophy, also known as renal rickets, is a type of kidney disease where the kidneys are unable to properly filter waste products from the blood. This can lead to the buildup of calcium and phosphate in the body, which can cause problems with bone health. Symptoms may include pain or swelling in the legs, as well as weakness or difficulty walking. Treatment for renal osteodystrophy typically involves managing the underlying kidney disease and addressing any associated bone problems through medications or other therapies.

Yes, dementia is a type of cognitive disorder that affects the brain and causes a decline in cognitive function. The term "cognitive disorder" refers to a group of conditions that affect the way the brain works and can lead to problems with memory, thinking, reasoning, perception, and language. Dementia is a common type of cognitive disorder that is characterized by a decline in cognitive abilities that interferes with daily life and activities.

There are several different types of dementia, including Alzheimer's disease, vascular dementia, Lewy body dementia, frontotemporal dementia, and more. Each type has its own specific symptoms and causes, but all forms of dementia ultimately result in a decline in cognitive function and impairment of daily life activities.

It's important to note that while dementia is a serious condition, there are ways to manage the symptoms and improve quality of life for those affected. This can include medications, therapies, support groups, and other resources specifically designed for individuals with dementia and their caregivers.
acquired hyperkeratosis is a condition in which the skin becomes thick and rough. It is also known as keratoderma, acquired.

tinea unguium is caused by fungal infections that affect the nails.
tinea unguium can cause thickening and separation of the nail plate from the nail bed.
tinea unguium can be treated with antifungal medications.

eumycotic mycetoma is a type of dermatomycosis that affects the skin and subcutaneous tissue in various locations, including the feet, trunk, buttocks, eyelids, lacrimal glands, paranasal sinuses, mandible, scalp, neck, perineum, and testes. It is characterized by the formation of nodules and can be accompanied by symptoms such as sinus discharge. Eumycotic mycetoma is also known as Madura foot, maduromycosis, mycotic mycetoma, eumycetoma, and has several other synonyms including Mycotic mycetoma and Mycosis fungoides palmaris.

It can be associated with systemic lupus erythematosus, rheumatic fever, and ligamentous laxity.

Lown-Ganong-Levine syndrome (LGLS), also known as atrial tachyarrhythmia with short P-R interval, is a condition characterized by an abnormal electrical communication from the atria to the ventricles through an accessory pathway. This can lead to supraventricular tachycardias and potentially life-threatening arrhythmias if not managed properly. The syndrome is named after its three discoverers: Dr. Eugene Lown, Dr. Paul Ganong, and Dr. Samuel Levine. It's important for patients with this condition to receive proper medical attention and follow any treatment recommendations provided by their healthcare provider to manage the symptoms and reduce the risk of complications.

Vertebral artery insufficiency, also known as Vertebral artery syndrome, is a type of artery disease that occurs when the vertebral arteries are unable to supply enough blood to the brain. This can lead to transient cerebral ischemia, which is a temporary lack of blood flow to the brain. It is not the same as Intersection Syndrome or any other specific disease, but rather a general condition that can be caused by a variety of factors such as age, injury, or underlying medical conditions.

Sneden syndrome, also known as Arteriovenous (AV) malformation, is a rare congenital disorder characterized by the presence of abnormal connections between arteries and veins. It can cause various symptoms depending on its location and size, such as hemodynamic instability, hypertension, proteinuria, and edema. Treatment options for Sneden syndrome may include surgical interventions, embolization, or a combination of both. It is important to consult with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and management of this condition.

Central Retinal Artery Occlusion (CRAO) is a type of retinal artery occlusion characterized by blockage of blood flow through the central retinal artery. This condition can lead to sudden vision loss and other complications if left untreated. It is important for individuals to seek medical attention immediately if they experience symptoms such as pain, redness, or decreased vision in one eye. Treatment options may include laser therapy, medication, or surgical intervention depending on the severity of the condition and other factors.

Moyamoya disease is a condition in which the arteries at the base of the brain become narrow, leading to reduced blood flow and potential complications like stroke. It can be caused by injury or atherosclerosis, among other things. It is also sometimes referred to as "sticky blood" due to the formation of blood clots in these constricted arteries.

Paronychia is a skin condition where the nail and skin meet at the side or base of a finger or toe nail. It can be caused by bacteria or fungus (Candida albicans) and can present with symptoms such as puss, thickening and discoloration of the nail plate.

Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis (FSGS) is a type of glomerulopathy characterized by the sclerosis of glomerular tufts. It primarily affects the juxtaposition between the glomerular basement membrane and the subepithelial space, leading to a thickening and subsequent occlusion of the filtration slits. FSGS is often seen in children and young adults and can be primary or secondary. Primary FSGS lacks an identifiable cause, while secondary FSGS occurs as a complication due to underlying medical conditions such as diabetes, hypertension, and lupus nephritis. The diagnosis of FSGS typically involves a combination of renal biopsy, urinalysis, and imaging studies. Treatment options for FSGS include medications to control proteinuria, antihypertensive agents, and immunosuppressive therapy in cases of secondary FSGS. In severe cases, dialysis or kidney transplantation may be necessary.

Protein deficiency anemia is a type of anemia that occurs when the body doesn't get enough protein. This can happen if someone isn't getting enough protein in their diet or if they are losing too much protein through their skin, nose, or other openings in the body. It can also occur due to certain medical conditions or genetic disorders that cause the body to have trouble absorbing protein from food. Symptoms of protein deficiency anemia include weakness, fatigue, pale skin, and difficulty concentrating. It is important to maintain a healthy diet and get enough protein through food to prevent this type of anemia.

Deficiency anemia, also known as iron-deficiency anemia, is a type of anemia characterized by insufficient amounts of iron in the body. Iron is an essential mineral that plays a vital role in red blood cell production and oxygen transportation. When the body does not have enough iron, it cannot produce enough healthy red blood cells, leading to anemia and its associated symptoms such as fatigue, weakness, paleness, and shortness of breath.

gonococcal spondylitis is a type of inflammation that occurs in the spine caused by the bacterium Neisseria gonorrhoeae. It is transmitted through sexual contact and can cause pain, stiffness, and limited mobility in the affected area.

Thank you for providing the definition of HELLP syndrome. To rephrase it in simpler terms, HELLP syndrome is a potentially life-threatening complication that can occur during pregnancy, characterized by high blood pressure, damage to red blood cells, liver dysfunction, and low platelet levels. It requires immediate medical attention and can lead to serious health risks for both the mother and the baby if left untreated.

Hordeolum externum is a type of blepharitis that affects the eyelashes. It occurs when the sebaceous glands at the base of the eyelashes become infected or when the apocrine sweat glands near the eyelid become inflamed. The exact synonym for Hordeolum externum is "external stye."

The disease Werdnig-Hoffmann disease, also known as spinal muscular atrophy 1 (SMA1), is a genetic disorder characterized by the progressive loss of motor neurons in the spinal cord, which leads to muscle weakness and atrophy. It primarily affects the legs, arms, shoulders, and respiratory muscles, and can lead to severe disability or even death if left untreated. The disease is caused by a deficiency of the protein survival motor neuron (SMN1), which is essential for the proper functioning of motor neurons. It can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that to develop the disease, an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. There is no cure for Werdnig-Hoffmann disease, but treatment options such as medications and assistive devices can help improve symptoms and increase quality of life.

Acute proliferative glomerulonephritis (APGN) is a type of nephritis that affects the kidneys. It is characterized by inflammation and proliferation of the glomerular basement membrane, leading to the formation of scar tissue and impairment of renal function. APGN can be caused by various factors such as infections, autoimmune disorders, and exposure to nephrotoxic drugs or substances. Symptoms of APGN include proteinuria, hematuria, edema, and hypertension. Diagnosis is typically made through a combination of medical history, physical examination, blood tests, and imaging studies such as renal biopsy. Treatment options for APGN may include medications to reduce inflammation and prevent further damage to the kidneys, as well as supportive care to manage symptoms and complications.

Suppurative uveitis is a type of uveitis that is characterized by inflammation and pus formation in the uvea, which are the pigmented layers of the eye. It typically causes symptoms such as pain, blurry vision, and redness in the eye. Suppurative uveitis can be caused by an infection, especially after surgery or a traumatic event.

Uveitis is a type of uveal disease that occurs when the inflammation affects one or more layers of the uvea in the eye. The uvea includes the iris, ciliary body, and choroid, which are all responsible for various functions such as focusing light on the retina and controlling the amount of light entering the eye. Uveitis can cause symptoms such as pain, redness, blurred vision, and sensitivity to light. If left untreated, it can lead to more serious complications such as blindness. It is important to consult an ophthalmologist if you experience any of these symptoms.

Esophageal candidiasis is a type of infection caused by the fungus Candida albicans. It occurs when the immune system is weakened, such as in people with HIV/AIDS or those receiving chemotherapy for cancer treatment. The infection can cause symptoms like difficulty swallowing, pain, and bleeding. It is also sometimes referred to as Candidal esophagitis, Candidiasis of the esophagus, esophageal moniliasis, or esophageal thrush.

Fungal esophagitis is a type of inflammation in the esophagus caused by fungi. It is considered to be a rare but serious condition that can cause difficulty swallowing, chest pain, and other symptoms. Treatment typically involves medications to suppress the immune system and kill the fungi, as well as dietary changes to avoid irritation of the esophagus. If left untreated, it can lead to severe complications such as narrowing of the esophagus or even cancer.

Acute cystitis, also known as acute interstitial nephritis, is a type of cystitis characterized by severe symptoms that develop suddenly. It is an inflammation of the renal pelvis and calyces due to dehydration, infections or other causes. The symptoms include severe pain in the back and sides, frequent urination, small amounts of urine, and a burning sensation when urinating.

Scrotum squamous cell carcinoma is a type of squamous cell carcinoma that is located in the scrotum. It is also known as scrotal squamous cell carcinoma. This type of cancer derives from squamous epithelial cells, which are found in the scrotum.

Scrotum melanoma is a specific type of melanoma that occurs in the scrotal region, which is the area around the testicles and the base of the penis. It is also known as scrotum neoplasm or melanoma of the scrotum. Melanocytes are specialized skin cells that produce melanin, a pigment that gives skin its color. When these cells become cancerous, they can produce excessive amounts of melanin and form malignant tumors. In the case of scrotum melanoma, it is believed to be caused by exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources, which can damage the skin cells and lead to cancer. If caught early, scrotum melanoma can be treated with surgery, but if left untreated, it can spread to nearby tissues and organs and become life-threatening. It is important for individuals to regularly check their own skin for any changes in color or texture, and to seek medical attention if they notice anything suspicious.

allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis is a type of respiratory allergy, which occurs when an individual's immune system reacts to the spores of Aspergillus moulds (A. fumigatus). This fungi can cause an allergic reaction in people with pre-existing respiratory conditions such as asthma or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). The symptoms of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis include wheezing, cough, fever, and chest pain. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have this condition, as it can lead to serious complications if left untreated.

prepuce cancer is a type of skin cancer that occurs in the foreskin, which is the skin that covers the head of the penis. It is also known as malignant neoplasm of foreskin or malignant tumor of foreskin.

Spermatic cord cancer, also known as testicular cancer or spermatogenic cell tumor, is a malignant growth that originates in the sperm-producing cells of the testicles. It is a type of male reproductive organ cancer and can affect both fertility and sexual function. The exact synonyms for spermatic cord cancer include malignant tumor of the Spermatic Cord, spermatic cord ca, and cancer of the spermatic cord. Treatment options may vary depending on the stage and location of the cancer but typically involve a combination of surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy.

Gout is a form of arthritis that affects the joints. It occurs when there is an excess of uric acid in the blood, which can cause crystals to form in the joint spaces and surrounding tissues, leading to inflammation and pain. Gout has been described as "the king of all gouts" due to its severity and potential long-term complications if left untreated. It is most commonly affecting the big toe, but can also affect other joints in the body such as ankles, knees, wrists, and elbows. Gout has been known since ancient times, with records dating back to Egypt and Greece.

Brain cancer is a type of central nervous system cancer that is characterized by the growth of abnormal cells in the tissues of the brain. It can be referred to as BT - Brain tumor, adult brain tumor, adult malignant brain neoplasm, brain neoplasm, malignant brain tumour, malignant primary brain neoplasm, malignant primary brain tumor, malignant tumor of the brain, neoplasm of the brain, primary brain neoplasm, primary brain tumor, or a primary malignant neoplasm of the brain. It can also be referred to as a tumor of the brain.

text: Nontoxic goiter is a type of goiter that does not cause any significant harm to the body and has no toxic effects. It results from an imbalance in the production of hormones by the thyroid gland, leading to enlargement or swelling of the thyroid gland. The symptoms are usually mild, such as a lump in the neck, hoarseness, and difficulty swallowing. Treatment for nontoxic goiter typically involves medications that regulate hormone production by the thyroid gland to reduce the size of the gland and alleviate symptoms. Surgery is rarely required but may be considered in severe cases or when the condition is causing significant discomfort or other complications.

Nodular goiter is a type of enlargement of the thyroid gland that occurs when thyroid tissue becomes abnormally solid or dense. It can cause symptoms such as swelling in the neck, difficulty breathing, and a hoarse voice. Nodular goiter is also sometimes referred to as nodular goitre. Other types of goiter include diffuse goiter and toxic goiter.
endemic goiter is a type of nutritional deficiency disease characterized by noncancerous enlargement of the thyroid gland due to an iodine deficiency.

Substernal goiter refers to an enlarged thyroid gland located in the lower part of the neck, below the level of the larynx. This condition is also known as retrosternal goiter or retrosternal thyroid goiter. It's important to note that substernal goiter and retrosternal thyroid goiter are synonymous terms that describe the same anatomical location and pathological process.

Substernal goiter can be caused by various factors, including autoimmune disorders, infections, medications, radiation exposure, or genetic predisposition. Symptoms of substernal goiter may include swelling or enlargement of the neck, difficulty swallowing, and hoarseness. Diagnosis typically involves a physical examination, thyroid function tests, and imaging studies such as ultrasound or computed tomography (CT).

Treatment options for substernal goiter depend on the underlying cause and severity of the condition. In some cases, medications may be prescribed to alleviate symptoms or address an autoimmune disorder. Surgical intervention, such as a thyroidectomy, may be necessary if the goiter is causing significant physical discomfort or other complications.

It's important for individuals with substernal goiter to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop an appropriate treatment plan and monitor their condition over time. Regular follow-up appointments and adherence to prescribed medications or therapies can help ensure the best possible outcomes and minimize the risk of complications.

That is correct. Proliferative diabetic retinopathy, also known as PDR, is a type of diabetic retinopathy that involves the growth of abnormal blood vessels in the retina. These blood vessels can cause hemorrhages, which can lead to vision loss if left untreated. Early detection and treatment are essential to prevent the progression of the disease.

background diabetic retinopathy is a type of diabetic eye disease.

Right Bundle Branch Block (RBBB) is a type of heart conduction disease characterized by a delay or blockage in the electrical signals that control the contractions of the heart muscle. It occurs when there is a problem with the electrical pathways within the heart, causing them to become slowed down or blocked.

It can be classified into two types: Left Bundle Branch Block (LBBB) and Right Bundle Branch Block (RBBB). LBBB affects the left side of the heart, while RBBB affects the right side. In RBBB, the electrical signals are delayed or blocked as they travel through the bundle of His, which is a group of specialized muscle cells in the wall of the heart that are responsible for coordinating the contractions of the atria and ventricles.

RBBB can be caused by a number of factors, including:

1. Coronary artery disease (CAD): This occurs when the blood vessels that supply the heart become narrowed or blocked due to the buildup of plaque made up of cholesterol and other substances.
2. Cardiomyopathy: This is a condition in which the heart muscle becomes weakened and unable to pump blood effectively. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetic causes, viral infections, and drug use.
3. Heart failure: When the heart fails to pump enough blood to meet the body's needs, it can lead to RBBB as the heart struggles to maintain a normal rhythm.
4. Electrolyte imbalances: In rare cases, an imbalance in electrolytes can cause RBBB.
5. Other causes include tumors and congenital heart defects.

RBBB is often diagnosed using an electrocardiogram (ECG), which records the electrical activity of the heart. Treatment for RBBB depends on the underlying cause, but it may include medications to improve heart function or rhythm control devices such as a pacemaker. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to repair any structural problems in the heart.

Hole retinal cyst is a type of degeneration of the macula and posterior pole, characterized by the presence of small fluid-filled cavities or pockets in the retina. These cysts can cause vision loss if they enlarge and lead to detachment of the retina. Hole retinal cysts are also known as Macular cysts, pseudoholes of retina, or simply holes in the retina. It is important to note that hole retinal cysts are not the same as age-related macular degeneration (AMD), which is a different condition that affects the central part of the retina and can cause vision loss due to damage to the photoreceptors.

submucous uterine fibroid refers to a type of uterine fibroid that is located adjacent to the lining of the uterus. It can cause various symptoms such as heavy bleeding, pelvic pain, and pressure on the bladder or rectum. Submucous leiomyoma of uterus is an exact synonym for submucous uterine fibroid.

Uterine fibroids are non-cancerous growths in the uterus that can cause various symptoms, such as heavy bleeding, pain, and bloating. They are also known as leiomyomas or uterine leiomyomas. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment of uterine fibroids.
oculoglandular tularemia is a type of tularemia that results in inflammation of the eyes and swelling of lymph glands in front of the ear.

Haverhill fever is a primary bacterial infectious disease that results from infection with Streptobacillus moniliformis. It can be transmitted through contact with urine or secretions from the mouth, eye, or nose of an infected animal, or by the bite of an infected animal, especially a rat. The symptoms of Haverhill fever include chills, fever, rash, and joint pain. It is also known as Streptobacillary fever, Streptobacillary rat-bite fever, or Streptobacillosis.

Lung cancer is a type of malignant neoplasm (cancerous tumor) that originates in the lung and affects the respiratory system. It can be classified into different subtypes, such as small cell lung cancer and non-small cell lung cancer, which vary in their size and behavior. Lung cancer is a leading cause of cancer death worldwide, accounting for approximately 1.6 million deaths annually. The risk factors associated with lung cancer include smoking, exposure to secondhand smoke, air pollution, occupational dust exposure, and certain genetic conditions. Early detection and treatment are crucial in improving the prognosis of lung cancer patients.

Tooth resorption is a medical condition where the tooth structure (hard tissue) deteriorates over time. It can be caused by various factors, including general aging, gum disease, and excessive exposure to acidic foods or drinks. Tooth resorption typically affects the roots of the teeth rather than the crown (the visible part of the tooth), causing the tooth to become weaker and more prone to fracturing or breaking. Treatment options may include dental procedures such as root canal therapy, gum surgery, and dental implants, depending on the severity of the condition. Proper oral hygiene practices, including regular brushing and flossing, can help prevent tooth resorption by maintaining overall oral health and reducing the risk of gum disease.

Behcet's disease is an autoimmune vasculitis that affects blood vessels throughout the body, leading to symptoms such as ulcerations on the mouth and genitals, as well as inflammation in the eye. It is also characterized by elevated levels of certain immunoglobulins and a triad of symptoms, which includes oral aphthous ulcers, genital ulcers, and uveitis. The disease has exact synonyms such as Adamantiades-Behcet disease, Behcet syndrome, Behet's syndrome, and triple symptom complex, and it is related to the Behcet's syndrome.

That is correct. A mucocele of the appendix, also known as an Appendicele Mucocele, is a type of intestinal disease that occurs when there is a buildup of mucus in the appendix. This condition can cause the appendix to become inflamed and swollen, which may lead to pain and discomfort. In some cases, it can also lead to more serious complications if left untreated. If you have any concerns about your health or are experiencing symptoms of a mucocele of the appendix, it is important to speak with a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Bronchus cancer, also known as bronchogenic carcinoma, is a type of lung cancer that originates in the bronchi or bronchiole cells. It is a malignant neoplasm characterized by uncontrolled cell growth and invasion of surrounding tissues. Bronchus cancer can occur at any age but is more common among smokers and individuals exposed to other environmental pollutants. Symptoms may include coughing, wheezing, shortness of breath, chest pain, and fatigue. Early detection and treatment are crucial for improving outcomes.

Diarrhea is a condition characterized by an abnormal increase in the frequency and/or volume of stool. It can be caused by bacterial, viral, or parasitic infections, as well as other factors such as medication side effects or excessive consumption of certain foods and liquids. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, cramping, bloating, gas, nausea, vomiting, fever, and fatigue. Diarrhea can lead to dehydration, especially in children and the elderly, and may require medical treatment to prevent complications such as electrolyte imbalances or rehydration solution overdose.

Diverticulitis of the colon is a medical condition characterized by the formation and inflammation of small pouches or sacs (diverticula) in the wall of the large intestine. This condition is also known as diverticular disease of the colon, and it can lead to symptoms such as abdominal pain, constipation, blood in the stool, and fever. It is important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment of this condition.

Typhoid fever is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that can be caused by Salmonella enterica subsp. enterica serovar Typhi. It is transmitted through the ingestion of contaminated food or water and can cause symptoms such as fever, diarrhea, prostration, headache, splenomegaly, liver enlargement, rose-colored spots, and leukopenia.

Porphyria is indeed an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by the accumulation of porphyrins, which are essential compounds involved in the production of heme. There are several types of porphyria, each with specific symptoms and underlying causes. The most common type is acute intermittent porphyria (AIP), which affects the nervous system and skin when heme is not properly synthesized. Other types include cutaneous porphyria, which primarily affects the skin, and neuroacanthocytosis, a rare form of porphyria that can cause neurological symptoms. Porphyria can be diagnosed through blood tests that measure the levels of porphyrins and other related compounds. Treatment may involve dietary changes, medications, or even hospitalization in severe cases. It's important to note that while rare, some forms of porphyria can be life-threatening if left untreated.

Hereditary coproporphyria is a type of acute porphyria that occurs due to a deficiency in the enzyme coproporphyrinogen oxidase. This results in an accumulation ofcoproporphyrin, which can cause neurological symptoms and other complications if left untreated. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the disease to develop. The exact synonyms for hereditary coproporphyria are Coproporphyrinogen oxidase deficiency and hereditary coproporphyria porphyria.

Erythropoietic Protoporphyria (EPP) is a form of acute porphyria that occurs due to the deficiency of the enzyme ferrochelatase, leading to abnormally high levels of protoporphyrin in the tissues. It causes symptoms such as skin fragility, blistering, and neurological problems. Treatment typically involves managing symptoms with medications and avoiding triggers.

Cutaneous porphyria is a specific type of porphyria that affects the skin. It is also known as Erythropoietic protoporphyria (EPP) because it interferes with the production of red blood cells in the bone marrow, causing an excess of protoporphyrin to build up in the body. EPP can cause symptoms such as sensitivity to sunlight, skin fragility, and pain or itching in the hands and feet. It is important for those with cutaneous porphyria to avoid exposure to sunlight and take steps to protect their skin from further damage.

klebsiella pneumonia is a type of bacterial pneumonia that involves an infection with the klebsiella pneumoniae bacteria. it can affect people who have underlying health conditions such as alcoholism, diabetes, or chronic lung disease and may present symptoms like high fever, cough, pleuritic chest pain, and hemoptysis.

Mycoplasma pneumoniae pneumonia is a type of bacterial pneumonia caused by the Mycoplasma pneumoniae bacteria. It can cause various symptoms such as chest pain, fever, headache, dry cough, and excessive sweating. It is also known by other names like Pneumonia due to Eaton's agent or cold agglutinin positive pneumonia.

Rift Valley fever is a type of viral infectious disease that results from infection with the Rift Valley fever virus, which is transmitted by Aedes mosquitoes. The virus affects both domestic animals and humans. Common symptoms of Rift Valley fever include jaundice, vomiting blood, passing blood in the feces, ecchymoses (bleeding under the skin), nose or gum bleeds, menorrhagia, and bleeding from venepuncture sites. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you may have Rift Valley fever as prompt treatment can improve outcomes.

Intestinal tuberculosis is a type of gastrointestinal tuberculosis, which refers to the infection of the intestines by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and gastrointestinal bleeding. It is characterized by diffuse mucosal fold thickening, formation of ulcers and fistulae in the intestine. The exact synonym for intestinal tuberculosis is tuberculosis of the intestine.

The term you are referring to is "optic disc drusen" or "drusen of the optic disc". Drusen are small, whitish-gray, slightly elevated areas that form in the tissue surrounding the optic nerve head. They are a normal part of aging and typically do not cause any symptoms. However, if they become numerous or grow in size, they can lead to vision loss. Drusen are often found in combination with other age-related changes in the eye, such as presbyopia and cataracts.

Vaginal Mullerian papilloma is a type of vaginal benign neoplasm.
Vaginal Mullerian papilloma presents in childhood and is considered to be of Mullerian origin.
Vaginal Muellerian papilloma has the same exact meaning as Vaginal Mullerian papilloma.

Scheuermann's disease is a type of spinal condition, specifically affecting the thoracic vertebrae. It occurs when there is abnormal bone growth and curvature in the thoracic spine, causing the upper back to curve forward. The disease is also known by other names such as Juvenile osteochondritis of the spine, Scheuermann's kyphosis, and Sherman's Disease.

Diphtheritic cystitis is a type of cystitis that occurs due to the infection of Corynebacterium diphtheriae bacteria, which can cause the formation of a thick, fibrinous membrane on the bladder mucosa. This condition can lead to symptoms such as painful urination, frequent urges to urinate, and blood in the urine. Diphtheritic cystitis is typically treated with antibiotics and may require hospitalization if severe.

Diphtheritic peritonitis is a type of peritonitis that is caused by the bacterium Corynebacterium diphtheriae. It is characterized by inflammation of the peritoneal cavity, which is the space that surrounds the abdominal organs. This type of peritonitis can be life-threatening if left untreated and requires prompt medical attention.

Exocrine pancreatic insufficiency (EPI) is a condition in which the exocrine gland of the pancreas does not produce enough digestive enzymes to properly break down food. This leads to abnormal digestion and can cause malabsorption of nutrients. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, steatorrhea (fatty stools), weight loss, and diarrhea. Treatment typically involves a combination of enzyme replacement therapy, dietary changes, and sometimes medications to manage symptoms. It is an important condition to manage as it can lead to other health complications if left untreated.

hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia is a type of hypoglycemia that occurs when there is too much insulin in the body. This can cause low blood sugar levels and can be a serious condition, especially if it is not properly managed.

Anatomical narrow angle borderline glaucoma is a type of borderline glaucoma that is characterized by an anatomically narrow anterior chamber angle with or without additional clinical features and risk factors associated with high likelihood of developing glaucomatous optic atrophy in the future. These additional features may include elevated intraocular pressure, retinal nerve fiber layer abnormalities, abnormal anterior chamber angles, and/or a positive family history for glaucoma without any evidence of current optic nerve atrophy.

Diabetic cataract is a type of cataract that occurs as a result of high blood sugar levels caused by diabetes. It is characterized by the loss of lens transparency and can lead to vision impairment if left untreated. It is important for individuals with diabetes to manage their blood sugar levels carefully in order to prevent the development of diabetic cataracts.

Hypertrophy of the tongue papillae, also known as Tongue papillary hypertrophy, is a condition where the small elevated growths on the tongue's surface become enlarged. These growths are called papillae and they are typically found along the top and sides of the tongue.

This condition can cause several symptoms, such as pain or discomfort when eating or swallowing, difficulty in speaking clearly, and an increased risk of developing infections or other tongue-related problems. It is important to consult a medical professional if you suspect you may have this condition. They will be able to provide a proper diagnosis and recommend appropriate treatment options.

It's worth noting that while this can be an uncomfortable condition, it is typically not serious and does not typically require long-term treatment. In most cases, it can be managed with simple lifestyle changes such as avoiding certain foods that may irritate the tongue or practicing good oral hygiene habits.

Congenital toxoplasmosis is a type of congenital infection that occurs when a woman is infected with the Toxoplasma gondii parasite during pregnancy. The parasite can be transmitted through contact with contaminated soil, food, or water, or by sexual transmission. If left untreated, congenital toxoplasmosis can cause serious complications for the developing fetus, including abnormal brain development and vision problems. However, with proper treatment, the risks associated with congenital toxoplasmosis can be minimized.

Laryngeal cartilage cancer is a type of larynx cancer that occurs when malignant cells grow and spread in the cartilage found in the larynx. The exact synonyms for this condition are "malignant neoplasm of laryngeal cartilage" and "malignant neoplasm of laryngeal cartilages." Another synonym is "malignant tumor of laryngeal cartilage." It's essential to note that the larynx, also known as the voice box, is a critical part of the human body responsible for producing and transmitting sound.

Yes, pedophilia is a type of paraphilia disorder, which involves a strong and persistent sexual attraction to children. The term "pedophilia" specifically refers to an adult's sexual interest in pre-pubescent children. It is important to note that the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM) no longer recognizes pedophilia as a distinct diagnosis, instead grouping it under the umbrella term "paraphilias not otherwise specified." This is because research has shown that many individuals who were previously diagnosed with pedophilia may actually have a condition called "hypersexual disorder" or other related paraphilias.

Ego dystonic sexual orientation, also known as same-sex attraction that one desires to change or suppress, is a type of sexual health disorder. This condition can cause significant distress and anxiety for the individual, as they may feel at odds with their own identity and desire to conform to societal expectations. Ego dystonic sexual orientation is characterized by the presence of negative emotions towards one's same-sex attraction, which leads to a desire to change or suppress it. It is important for individuals experiencing ego dystonic sexual orientation to seek professional help and support to address their feelings and work towards a more accepting and inclusive perspective on their sexuality.

Senile ectropion is a type of ectropion that occurs as a result of aging. Involutional ectropion, on the other hand, refers specifically to the sagging of the eyelid due to the natural aging process. While both conditions can lead to a droopy appearance and impaired vision, they are distinct conditions with different causes and treatments. Senile ectropion is typically caused by weakened connective tissue and muscle changes that occur as we age, while involutional ectropion is the result of the natural aging process that affects the eyelid's support structure. Treatment options for senile ectropion may include surgical procedures such as blepharoplasty or laser resurfacing to tighten and lift the eyelids, while involutional ectropion is best treated with conservative measures such as using eye drops to manage symptoms or wearing eyeglasses to help support the eyelid.

Chondromalacia patellae, also known as "runner's knee" or "jumper's knee," is a common condition that affects the patella (kneecap) and surrounding cartilage. It occurs when the cartilage in the knee becomes soft and swollen, causing pain and inflammation. This condition can be caused by overuse or injury to the knee joint.

Treatment options for chondromalacia patellae include rest, ice, compression, and elevation (RICE) to reduce pain and inflammation, physical therapy to strengthen muscles around the knee, and medical devices such as braces or supports to help stabilize the joint. Surgical intervention is rare but may be necessary in severe cases where the patella has shifted out of place or other damage has occurred.

It's important to consult a healthcare professional if you suspect you have chondromalacia patellae, as early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further damage and improve symptoms.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a genetic disorder that affects the body's connective tissue, which includes collagen. It causes highly flexible joints, elastic skin, and excessive bruising due to poor collagen production. There are several subtypes of EDS, each with unique symptoms. The five cardinal signs seen in all subtypes include skin fragility, blood vessel fragility, skin hyperelasticity, joint hypermobility, and characteristic subcutaneous nodules. Other synonyms for EDS include Cutis hyperelastica and Elastic skin.

Correct. Reading disorder, also known as dyslexia, is a learning disability that affects an individual's ability to read and comprehend text. It is characterized by difficulties in phonemic awareness, decoding, and fluency. These difficulties can make it challenging for individuals with reading disorder to read accurately and efficiently. However, with proper support and intervention strategies, people with reading disorders can improve their reading skills and overcome the challenges they face.

Stiff person syndrome is a movement disorder characterized by progressive rigidity and muscle stiffness, which can affect various parts of the body. It's also known as stiff-man syndrome or just stiff man syndrome. The exact cause of this condition is unknown, but it is believed to be autoimmune in nature. Symptoms may include pain, weakness, and limited mobility, and treatment often involves medications to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Tinea profunda is a type of infection caused by the fungus Trichophyton mentagrophytes, which can result in the formation of subcutaneous abscesses. It is also known as deep seated dermatophytosis, granuloma trichophyticum, and Majocchi's granuloma.

tinea manuum is a type of skin disease.
tinea manuum is a type of dermatophytosis that results in a fungal skin infection located on the hand. It has a material basis in Ascomycota fungi that belong to a group called dermatophytes and can cause symptoms such as itching, burning, cracking, and scaling.
It is also known as Dermatophytosis of the hand or Tinea manus.

scrub typhus is a type of illness that is caused by the bacterium Rickettsia tsutsugamushi and is transmitted through the bites of trombiculid mites (Leptotrombidium deliense). It presents with symptoms such as fever, headache, muscle pain, cough, maculopapular rash, eschar, splenomegaly, and lymphadenopathy. The illness is also known by other names like Japanese river fever, Kedani fever, Scrub mite-borne typhus, Tsutsugamushi disease, Chigger-borne rickettsiosis, Mite-borne rickettsiosis, and Tropical typhus.

alpha 1 antitrypsin deficiency is a condition in which the body doesn't produce enough of the protein alpha-1 antitrypsin. This can cause problems with the proteins that are involved in breaking down other proteins and can also lead to inflammation and damage in the lungs and liver. It is inherited and can be passed down through families. Treatment may include medications to help replace the missing protein or prevent further damage.

Fibrodysplasia ossificans progressiva is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the gradual replacement of muscle and connective tissue with bone. It is caused by mutations in the ACVR1 gene, which is located on the long (q) arm of chromosome 4 at position 31. The condition can be inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a person has an increased risk of developing the disorder if one or both of their parents pass on the mutated gene. Symptoms typically begin in childhood and adolescence and may include muscle pain, limited movement, and bone growths called exostoses. Treatment options for FOP include physical therapy, medications to reduce inflammation and pain, and occasionally surgery to remove the affected areas.

Temporal arteritis, also known as giant cell arteritis, is a type of autoimmune disease that primarily affects the blood vessels in the head, particularly those supplying the temples. It is characterized by inflammation of the lining of the blood vessels and can cause symptoms such as headache, jaw pain, and visual disturbances. Temporal arteritis is considered a central nervous system vasculitis and is often associated with elevated levels of immunoglobulin in the affected individual. It has also been referred to as Horton's disease, though this term is less commonly used today.

Kawasaki disease, also known as MLNS, is a type of acute febrile mucocutaneous lymph node syndrome characterized by fever, inflammation of medium-sized blood vessels in the body, and swelling of cervical lymph nodes. It often affects infants and young children, and can also cause symptoms such as conjunctival congestion, reddening of the lips and oral cavity, edema of extremities, and protrusion of tongue papillae. Kawasaki disease is not contagious and there is no specific treatment for it but antibiotics and corticosteroids have been shown to help reduce inflammation.

Congenital dyserythropoietic anemia, also known as congenital dyshaematopoietic anemia, is a type of congenital hemolytic anemia. Congenital hemolytic anemia refers to a group of disorders in which red blood cells (RBCs) are destroyed faster than they can be replaced by the bone marrow. This leads to a decrease in the number of RBCs and a lower-than-normal level of hemoglobin in the blood, causing anemia. In congenital dyserythropoietic anemia, this occurs due to a problem with erythropoiesis, which is the process by which the body produces red blood cells. The decrease in RBCs and hemoglobin can be caused by genetic mutations or other factors that interfere with normal erythropoiesis.

Pernicious anemia is a type of nutritional deficiency disease that affects the body's ability to produce or absorb vitamin B12. This can lead to a decrease in red blood cells and cause symptoms such as fatigue, pallor, shortness of breath, ataxia, paresthesia, and glossitis. It is caused by an autoimmune disorder affecting the production or function of intrinsic factor, which is needed for vitamin B12 absorption, or genetic factors. It can be diagnosed through a blood test that measures the levels of vitamin B12 and other nutrients in the body. Treatment may involve supplements to increase the body's intake of vitamin B12 and dietary changes to ensure proper absorption.

Megaloblastic anemia is a type of macrocytic anemia, which refers to a deficiency in the production of red blood cells due to an imbalance in DNA synthesis during their production. There are several types of megaloblastic anemia, including recessive hereditary megaloblastic anemia 1, also known as IGS (Imerslund-Grasbeck syndrome). Other synonyms for this condition include RH-MGA1, MGA1 Norwegian type, and megaloblastic anaemia.

Gastrointestinal anthrax is a type of anthrax disease, which refers to an infection caused by the bacterium Bacillus anthracis that affects the gastrointestinal tract. It can result in symptoms such as severe diarrhea, vomiting, hematemesis (vomiting blood), and loss of appetite. The disease is typically transmitted through the ingestion of contaminated meat. Gastrointestinal anthrax has a mortality rate of up to 60% if left untreated.

Labia majora carcinoma refers to a type of vulva cancer that occurs in the outer labial tissues. The term "labia majora" is used to describe the outer lips of the female genitalia, which are located on either side of the vagina. This type of cancer can develop in these outer labial tissues and may spread to other areas of the body if left untreated. It's important to note that while this term might be medically accurate, it is not a common or everyday way of referring to vulva cancer.

Diamond-Blackfan anemia is a rare congenital disorder characterized by a lack of red blood cells (anemia) due to a deficiency in erythroid progenitors in the bone marrow. The condition is often diagnosed during early childhood and can be associated with other complications, such as growth retardation, limb deformities, and an increased risk of leukemia. It has been found to be caused by mutations in one or more of the following genes: RPS19, EIF3E, EIF2S1, DNM1, BRD4, and RANK.

Color blindness is a condition where an individual has difficulty seeing color or perceiving color differences. It can be caused by various factors such as genetics, diseases, or injury to the eyes. There are different types and degrees of color blindness, which can affect an individual's ability to see certain colors or shades. In some cases, it may not cause significant impairment, while in others, it can impact daily activities and tasks that require accurate color perception. It is important for individuals with color blindness to adapt their lifestyle accordingly and use tools and aids that can help them navigate their environment more effectively.
Vaginal glandular tumor is a type of vaginal cancer that has a material basis in glandular tissue.

Pure red cell aplasia (PRCA) is also known as:

1. Red cell hypoplasia
2. Primary red cell aplasia
3. Pure red cell aplasia

Sarcoidosis is a disease that affects various organs in the body, including the skin. It is characterized by the inflammation of the lymph nodes and the formation of granulomas (clumps of immune cells). When sarcoidosis affects the skin, it is referred to as cutaneous sarcoidosis or skin sarcoidosis. It can cause skin rashes, bumps on the skin, and other skin changes. In some cases, it can also affect the eyes, lungs, heart, and nervous system. It is not clear what causes sarcoidosis, but it is thought to be an autoimmune disease that occurs when the immune system becomes overactive and attacks healthy cells in the body. Treatment options include medications, such as corticosteroids and immunosuppressants, to help reduce inflammation and other symptoms of sarcoidosis.

Neurosarcoidosis is a type of sarcoidosis that affects the nervous system, characterized by involvement of the cranial nerves, diffuse meningeal disease, acute polyneuropathy, myelitis, or hypothalamic pituitary axis malformation. It develops from a type IV hypersensitivity reaction with non-caseating granulomas involving the nervous system.

Uveoparotid fever is a type of sarcoidosis characterized by unilateral facial nerve palsy, parotid gland enlargement, anterior uveitis, and low-grade fever. It develops from a Type IV hypersensitivity reaction with noncaseating granulomatous infiltration of especially the parotid glands which compresses the facial nerve. Uveoparotid fever is also known as Heerfordt's syndrome.

Cardiac sarcoidosis is a type of sarcoidosis that involves the heart and can lead to symptoms such as heart failure. It is characterized by non-caseating granulomas infiltrating the myocardial tissue, especially in the left ventricle, and can result from a type IV hypersensitivity reaction.

pulmonary sarcoidosis is a type of sarcoidosis, which is characterized by noncaseating granulomatous infiltration of the lungs and supporting lymph nodes, bilateral hilar adenopathy, and pulmonary issues. It has symptoms such as shortness of breath, fatigue, wheezing, and chronic cough, and develops from a type IV hypersensitivity reaction. It is also known as lung sarcoidosis.

hepatic encephalopathy is a type of brain disease that occurs as a complication of liver disease, such as cirrhosis. It is characterized by loss of brain function, the occurrence of confusion, altered level of consciousness, and coma. The exact synonym for hepatic encephalopathy is Portal-systemic encephalopathy.

Alexia, also known as word blindness or text blindness, is a type of agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to recognize written words. It can be caused by brain damage or other neurological disorders, and it is often characterized by difficulty in reading, writing, and spelling.

Aphemismetasia is another term for word blindness that is often used interchangeably with Alexia. Acquired dyslexia, on the other hand, refers to a type of dyslexia that is acquired later in life rather than being present at birth or during early childhood development.

It's important to note that while these terms may be used interchangeably in some contexts, they each have their own specific meaning and should be used accordingly when discussing the various types of agnosia and related conditions.

Congenital hypoplastic anemia is a type of physical disorder that occurs when the bone marrow does not develop properly in the fetus. It can lead to a lack of red blood cells, which can cause anemia and other health problems. It is also known as congenital aplastic anemia, which means that the bone marrow is unable to produce enough blood cells. This condition can be inherited or acquired, and it can affect people of all ages. It is important for those with this condition to receive proper medical care to manage their symptoms and improve their quality of life.

Urethritis is a type of urethral disease.
Non-Gonococcal Urethritis (NGU) and Nongonococcal urethritis are exact synonyms for this condition.

Bejel is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that has symptoms such as moist patches in the mouth and lumps in long bones. It is caused by the bacterium Treponema pallidum subsp endemicum and can be transmitted through contact or sharing of domestic utensils. The infection can lead to disfigurement and deformed bones if left untreated. Bejel has an exact synonym for Njovera and Nonvenereal endemic syphilis.
Glanders is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results in septicemic

Basilar artery occlusion refers to the obstruction or blockage of the basilar artery, which is a blood vessel located at the base of the brain. This condition can lead to a lack of blood flow to certain areas of the brain, causing potential damage and negative effects on cognitive function, vision, balance, and other functions. It is considered a type of cerebrovascular disease and can be caused by various factors such as atherosclerosis, emboli, or trauma. It is essential to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or someone else may have experienced basilar artery occlusion.

Corneal argyrosis is a type of corneal disease characterized by the deposition of white, waxy material in the cornea. This condition can cause visual impairment and is often associated with aging. It is also sometimes referred to as Argentous corneal deposits or Argyrosis of the cornea.

posterior corneal pigmentation is a type of corneal deposit.
posterior corneal pigmentation has exact synonym Posterior corneal pigmentations.

coccidioidomycosis is a type of primary systemic mycosis that results in a systemic fungal infection, has a material basis in Coccidioides immitis, is transmitted by airborne spores and causes symptoms such as conjunctivitis, arthritis, chest pain and the formation of skin nodules.

Gonococcal bursitis is a type of bursitis that occurs as a result of infection by the Neisseria gonorrhoeae bacterium. It is commonly found in the tendons and joints, particularly those in the knees, ankles, and elbows. The infection can cause inflammation, pain, and stiffness in the affected areas, making it difficult to move or perform daily activities. Treatment typically involves antibiotics to kill the bacteria causing the infection, as well as rest, ice, and elevation to reduce inflammation and promote healing. In severe cases, physical therapy may be necessary to regain strength and flexibility in the affected areas.

Gonococcal synovitis and tenosynovitis are inflammatory conditions that affect the joints and tendons. They are caused by infection with Neisseria gonorrhoeae, a type of bacteria that can be transmitted through sexual contact or other close physical contact. Symptoms may include pain, swelling, and limited movement in the affected joints and tendons. Treatment typically involves antibiotics to clear the infection and rest to allow the inflammation to resolve. Prevention strategies include practicing safe sex, avoiding close physical contact with others who have gonorrhea or other STIs, and maintaining personal hygiene.

Correct. Urethral intrinsic sphincter deficiency, also known as Intrinsic (urethral) sphincter deficiency (ISD), is a type of urethral disease characterized by the loss or dysfunction of the internal urethral sphincters that help maintain continence. This condition can lead to urinary incontinence, which is the involuntary loss of urine. In some cases, it may also be associated with other conditions such as urethral stricture or pelvic organ prolapse. Treatment options for ISD typically involve medical management and lifestyle changes to help improve bladder control and prevent further complications.

central pterygium is a type of progressive peripheral pterygium that is characterized by the gradual thickening and growth of conjunctiva, which can eventually cause astigmatism. It may also be accompanied by symptoms such as foreign body sensation, decreased vision, and fleshy bumps on the surface of the eye. These growths are more common in individuals prone to ocular surface injury due to exposure to sunlight, heat, or dry environments. Central pterygium is often considered a precursor to pinguecula and can progress from one to the other over time.

Progressive peripheral pterygium is a type of conjunctival pterygium. It is characterized by progressive (as opposed to quiescent) fleshy outpouching of conjunctival growth and has symptoms such as fleshy bumps on the surface of the eye, foreign body sensation, decreased vision, and astigmatism. These pterygiums are more common in people prone to ocular surface injury, such as those living in sunny, hot, and dry climates and progress from pinguecula.

Supraglottis cancer is a type of larynx cancer that occurs in the supraglottic part of the larynx, which is the area above the glottis. It is also known as cancer of the extrinsic larynx or malignant neoplasm of the supraglottis. Symptoms may include hoarseness, difficulty swallowing, and a feeling of something being stuck in the throat. Treatment options for supraglottis cancer may include surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy. It is important to consult with a healthcare professional if you suspect you have symptoms of supraglottis cancer.

Balanitis xerotica obliterans, also known as Penile Lichen Sclerosus, is a type of balanitis characterized by white plaques or patches on the genitals. It has exact synonyms for this condition include MESH:D052798.

Thanatophoric dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia.
Thanatophoric dysplasia has the definition An osteochondrodysplasia that results in short arms and legs with excess folds of skin.
Thanatophoric dysplasia has an exact match MESH:D013796.

Proteus syndrome is a rare genetic condition that can affect many parts of the body, including bones, skin, and internal organs. It is caused by mutations in the PTEN gene, which is responsible for regulating cell growth and preventing the development of tumors. People with Proteus syndrome may experience excessive growth and overgrowth of various tissues, as well as an increased risk of developing tumors, particularly in the skin and other organs. The condition can also affect the immune system and lead to the development of certain blood disorders. Treatment for Proteus syndrome typically involves a multidisciplinary approach that includes surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy, depending on the specific needs of the individual.

Childhood disintegrative disease is a type of pervasive developmental disorder, which is characterized by late onset (greater than 3 years of age) of developmental delays in language, social function, and motor skills. It affects children who have had previously normal development but then appear to regress. The condition was first described by Heller in 1941 and has since been referred to as Heller's syndrome or Disintegrative psychosis. However, it is now recognized that these terms are not entirely accurate and the disorder is better understood as a type of pervasive developmental disorder, with its own unique set of characteristics and symptoms.

Cochleovestibular Meniere's disease is a type of Meniere's disease that affects the inner ear and can cause symptoms like vertigo, tinnitus, and hearing loss. It is also known as active Menière's disease because it causes symptoms that are more severe and disabling than those associated with other types of Meniere's disease. The exact synonym for Cochleovestibular Meniere's disease is "active cochleovestibular Meniere's disease" or simply "active Menière's disease, cochleovestibular." It can be diagnosed through a hearing test and an MRI of the inner ear. Treatment typically involves medications to manage symptoms and prevent future attacks, such as diuretics, antivertigo medication, and calcium channel blockers.
Active Vestibular Meniere's Disease is a type of Meniere's disease that affects the vestibular system, causing symptoms such as dizziness and balance problems.

Cochlear Meniere's disease, also known as active cochlear Menière's disease, is a type of Meniere's disease that affects the inner ear and causes symptoms such as hearing loss, tinnitus, and vertigo. It is characterized by fluctuations in hearing and balance, and can be caused by various factors including genetics, age, and certain medications. Treatment for Cochlear Menière's disease typically involves a combination of medical therapies and lifestyle changes to manage symptoms and prevent further complications.

Jejunal cancer is a type of small intestine cancer that occurs in the jejunum, which is the part of the small intestine responsible for absorbing nutrients. It is also known as malignant neoplasm of the jejunum or malignant tumor of the jejunum.

Benign vaginal carcinosarcoma is a type of benign neoplasm that affects the vagina. It is characterized by having both epithelial and connective tissue components, which are both considered to be abnormal growths in the vagina. This type of neoplasm is typically not life-threatening and can be treated with surgery or other non-invasive procedures.

Paranasal sinus benign neoplasm refers to a noncancerous growth or tumor found in the paranasal sinuses. The paranasal sinuses are hollow spaces located near the skull base, and include the maxillary, ethmoid, frontal, sphenoid, and anterior cranial fossa sinuses.

A benign neoplasm is a type of growth or tumor that is noncancerous, meaning it does not have the ability to spread to other parts of the body or cause metastasis. However, while benign neoplasms are generally less aggressive than cancerous tumors, they can still cause problems if left untreated, as they can continue to grow and put pressure on surrounding tissues and organs, such as the brain or eye.

Paranasal sinus benign neoplasm is often treated with surgery, although radiation therapy may also be used in some cases. The type of treatment recommended will depend on the exact location and size of the tumor, as well as the patient's overall health and medical history.

That is correct! Hairy tongue, also known as glossitis, occurs when the filiform papillae on the tongue's surface become overgrown or hyperplastic. This can cause an abnormal appearance of the tongue and may be associated with certain underlying medical conditions or medications. It is important to consult a healthcare professional if you suspect you have hairy tongue or any other oral health concerns.

Moebius syndrome is a genetic disorder characterized by facial weakness and limited eye movement. It can affect both sides of the face (bilateral) or just one side (unilateral). The condition is usually present at birth and does not get worse over time. It has been linked to certain genetic mutations, but the exact cause in most cases remains unknown. Moebius syndrome is also known as Mobius syndrome and can be part of a larger spectrum of conditions called the Oromandibular-limb hypogenesis spectrum.

Tuberous sclerosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by the growth of numerous noncancerous tumors in many parts of the body. It has exact synonyms such as Bourneville's disease, Epiloia, Tuberose sclerosis, and Tuberous sclerosis syndrome. Additionally, it can also be referred to as cerebral sclerosis.

Paranasal sinus disease refers to any inflammation or infection of the paranasal sinuses, which are a group of hollow spaces within the skull adjacent to the nasal cavity. These sinuses include the maxillary, ethmoid, sphenoid, and frontal sinuses. Nasal sinus disease specifically refers to inflammation or infection of the nasal sinuses. Paranasal sinus disease is a type of nasal sinus disease, but not all cases of paranasal sinus disease are necessarily nasal sinus diseases.

Tetanus neonatorum is a severe form of tetanus that occurs in newborn babies. It is caused by the bacterium Clostridium tetani, which enters the baby's body through the unclean blade used to cut the umbilical cord or substances applied to the cord stump that contain bacteria. The symptoms of tetanus neonatorum include muscle stiffness, spasms, difficulty breathing, exhaustion, and sometimes even death if not treated promptly. It is important for newborns to receive an injection of tetanus toxoid within the first 24 hours of life to protect them against this potentially fatal infection.

Loiasis is a type of filariasis, which is characterized by parasitic infection of the skin and eyes caused by the nematode Loa loa. It is transmitted through the bite of a deer fly or mango fly, and the disease is marked by episodic angioedema in the arms and legs, cyst-like enlargements of connective tissue around muscle sheaths, and dead worms causing chronic abscesses that may lead to granulomatous reactions and fibrosis.

Osteopetrosis is a type of osteosclerosis. Osteosclerosis refers to the excessive thickening and hardening of bone tissue. Osteopetrosis occurs when there is an increased rate of bone formation relative to bone resorption, resulting in abnormal accumulation of calcium and phosphate within the bone tissue. This leads to the formation of dense, hard, and brittle bones, which can result in osteopetrosis. Another name for this condition is Albers-Schonberg disease or marble bone.

purulent labyrinthitis is a condition where the inner ear is infected by bacteria, leading to symptoms such as deafness and dizziness. It usually occurs as a complication of other infections, such as acute otitis media or purulent meningitis. The exact synonyms for this condition include suppurative labyrinthitis, bacterial labyrinthitis, and acute suppurative labyrinthitis.

Corneal squamous cell carcinoma is a type of squamous cell carcinoma that affects the cornea. It is also known as corneal epidermoid carcinoma. The cornea is the clear, protective outer layer of the eye and is responsible for focusing light onto the retina. Squamous cell carcinoma is a type of cancer that begins in the squamous cells of the skin or other tissues. It typically occurs in areas exposed to sunlight and can be caused by long-term sun exposure. While corneal squamous cell carcinoma is relatively uncommon, it can cause significant vision loss if left untreated. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, or a combination of both.

Hyperparathyroidism is a condition in which the parathyroid glands produce too much parathyroid hormone (PTH). This can lead to an increased calcium level in the blood, and may cause symptoms such as fatigue, weakness, and bone pain. In some cases, it can also affect the kidneys and increase the risk of kidney stones. It is typically diagnosed through blood tests and imaging studies, and treated with surgery to remove the overactive glands.
Low tension glaucoma (LTG) is a type of open-angle

Secondary Parkinson's disease, also known as Symptomatic Parkinsonism or Disorder Presenting Primarily with Parkinsonism, is a type of neurodegenerative disorder. It is characterized by the gradual decline in dopamine-producing neurons in the brain, leading to symptoms similar to those seen in primary Parkinson's disease. However, unlike primary Parkinson's disease, which is genetic and progressive, secondary Parkinson's disease is caused by other factors such as medication side effects or exposure to certain toxins. It is essential to work with a healthcare provider to diagnose and manage secondary Parkinson's disease effectively.

Interval angle-closure glaucoma (IACG) is a type of primary angle-closure glaucoma characterized by acute closure of the anterior chamber angle by an intrinsic defect, resulting in blocked aqueous outflow and elevated intraocular pressure. It typically resolves spontaneously after several hours but may recur. Symptoms include sudden pain, redness, headache, and blurry vision with haloes around lights. IACG can be exacerbated by medications or states that dilate the eyes and narrow the anterior chamber angle, blocking aqueous outflow. It has exact synonyms such as Angle-closure glaucoma, subacute; Intermittent angle-closure glaucoma; and Prodromal angle closure glaucoma.

Paranasal Sinus Lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the paranasal sinuses, which are located in the skull and are part of the nasal cavity. It is also known as Lymphoma of Accessory sinus or Lymphoma of Paranasal sinus.

angle closure glaucoma is a type of glaucoma that affects the optic nerve and can cause a loss of vision. It occurs when the drainage angle between the iris and cornea becomes blocked, leading to increased pressure in the eye. Common symptoms include pain, redness, headache, and blurry vision. Angle closure glaucoma is typically treated with medication or surgery to help improve blood flow and reduce pressure on the optic nerve.

subserous uterine fibroid is a type of uterine fibroid.
subserous uterine fibroid has definition An uterine fibroid that is located adjacent to the outside of the uterus..
subserous uterine fibroid has exact synonym subserous leiomyoma of uterus..

Optic disk drusen, also known as optic nerve head drusen, is a condition characterized by the accumulation of fluid in the optic nerve head. This can cause swelling and pressure on the surrounding nerves, which may lead to vision loss if left untreated. In addition to optic disk drusen, there are other types of optic nerve diseases that can cause vision problems, such as ischemic optic neuropathy and traumatic optic neuropathy. It's important for individuals who experience vision changes or other symptoms to seek medical attention in order to receive a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.

Aspergillosis is a type of opportunistic infection caused by Aspergillus, a genus of mold. It can affect various organs and tissues in the body, including the lungs, brain, kidney, heart, bone, eyes, sinuses, skin, and gastrointestinal tract. It is more likely to occur in individuals with weakened immune systems, such as those undergoing chemotherapy or taking steroids. Symptoms can include fever, chest pain, shortness of breath, and fatigue. In severe cases, it can be life-threatening.

Neuroaspergillosis is a type of disease that affects the nervous system, and it can occur when a person's immune system is weakened. It is caused by the fungus Aspergillus, which can infect the central nervous system in immunocompromised patients. When this happens, it can lead to a space-occupying lesion, which can cause symptoms such as headache, fever, and nausea. Neuroaspergillosis is an aspergillosis that involves fungal infection of the central nervous system in immunocompromised patients caused by Aspergillus.

Cortical senile cataract is a type of cataract that occurs as a result of aging. It is characterized by the opacification, or clouding, of the lens cortex, which can cause vision loss if left untreated. Cortical senile cataracts are also sometimes referred to as age-related cataracts because they are so strongly associated with aging.

Twin to twin transfusion syndrome, also known as FTTTS, is a type of neonatal anemia that occurs when one or more fetuses in the womb receive too much blood from their twin. It is caused by a lack of proper nutrition and oxygen supply in the placenta. This can result in fetal hemorrhage into the co-twin, leading to anemia. The symptoms of FTTTS include low birth weight, jaundice, and decreased urine output. It is important for healthcare providers to monitor pregnancies closely and provide appropriate treatment to ensure the healthiest outcome for both the mother and the fetuses involved.

The maxillary sinus is one of the paranasal sinuses, which are hollow spaces found within the bones of the face, near the nasal cavity. These benign neoplasms can cause problems such as congestion, blockages, and pain due to their size and location. They are typically treated with surgery or other minimally invasive techniques.

That is correct! Cholestasis refers to a blockage or obstruction in the bile ducts, which prevents bile from flowing properly. This can lead to problems such as jaundice and other liver-related issues. It's important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have cholestasis, as it can be treated with medication or other interventions.

Alveolar periostitis, also known as Alveolitis of the jaw or Dry socket, is a type of periostitis that occurs when there is damage to the jawbone around an extracted tooth. It can cause severe pain and inflammation in the affected area. Treatment typically involves antibiotics, pain relief medication, and keeping the affected area clean. It's essential to maintain good oral hygiene practices to prevent future complications.

Female infertility can be caused by a variety of factors, including hormonal imbalances, blocked fallopian tubes, and endometriosis. In some cases, female infertility is caused by uterine disease, which can make it difficult for a woman to get pregnant. Uterine diseases that can cause female infertility include fibroids, polyps, and adhesions. Other possible causes of female infertility include age, weight, and smoking. It is important for women who are having trouble getting pregnant to speak with a healthcare provider about their options, which may include medications, surgery, or assisted reproductive technologies such as in vitro fertilization (IVF).

Eclampsia is a pregnancy complication characterized by high blood pressure. It can also cause seizures and swelling in the legs and ankles. Eclampsia can occur during or after childbirth and is typically treated with medication to manage blood pressure and prevent further complications.

vaginal carcinosarcoma is a type of vaginal cancer that has a mixed origin, consisting of both epithelial and mesenchymal tissue. This is in contrast to other types of vaginal cancer, which have a more uniform cellular composition. The exact synonyms for vaginal carcinosarcoma include malignant vaginal mixed epithelial and mesenchymal tumor, vaginal malignant mixed Mullerian tumor, vaginal malignant mixed mesodermal (mullerian) tumor, and vaginal mixed epithelial and mesenchymal tumor.

Frontal sinus cancer is a type of malignant neoplasm or tumor that occurs in the frontal sinus, which is one of the four paranasal sinuses located in the skull. This condition is considered to be a form of paranasal sinus cancer. It is important to note that while the term "frontal sinus cancer" is often used, it may not always accurately describe the disease as some literature refers to it as malignant neoplasm of frontal sinus or malignant tumor of frontal sinus instead. In any case, frontal sinus cancer is a serious condition that requires prompt medical attention and treatment.

Obstructive jaundice is a type of cholestasis characterized by yellowish pigmentation of the skin and sclera due to high bilirubin levels resulting from biliary tract obstruction. It has the following exact synonyms: Cholestatic Jaundice, Cholestatic jaundice syndrome, and Obstructive hyperbilirubinemia.

biliary atresia has the exact synonym Atresia of bile duct.
biliary atresia has the exact synonym Congenital biliary atresia.

Frontal sinus benign neoplasm is a type of paranasal sinus benign neoplasm, which occurs in the frontal sinus region. It can also be referred to as a neoplasm of the frontal sinus or tumor of the Frontal sinus.

Extrahepatic cholestasis is a type of cholestasis that occurs due to blockages in the bile ducts located outside the liver. It can be caused by various factors such as tumors, gallstones, inflammation, or other abnormalities in the biliary system.

Paranasal sinus sarcoma is a rare type of cancer that affects the paranasal sinuses, which are air-filled cavities in the skull surrounding the nose. It is classified as a sarcoma, which is a type of cancer that develops from connective tissue such as bone or cartilage. Paranasal sinus sarcoma can be difficult to diagnose and treat due to its location and rarity. It is important for doctors to have expertise in this area when treating patients with this condition. In some cases, a biopsy may be necessary to confirm the diagnosis. If you or someone you know has been diagnosed with paranasal sinus sarcoma, it's essential to seek out specialized treatment from experienced professionals as soon as possible to ensure the best chance of recovery.
