Pleuropneumonia is a type of pneumonia characterized by the inflammation of the pleura, which is the lining surrounding the lungs, and the accumulation of pus in the pleural space. This can be caused by bacterial infections and can result in symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, and fever. It's important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have pleuropneumonia to receive proper treatment.

Blindness is a type of eye disease that occurs when the eyes are unable to properly process visual information, resulting in a loss or diminished vision. It can be caused by various factors such as genetics, aging, injury, or diseases affecting the optic nerve or retina. There are different degrees and types of blindness, ranging from legal blindness (20/200 visual acuity or worse) to total blindness (no light perception). Treatment options for blindness depend on the underlying cause but may include medications, surgery, and assistive technology such as guide dogs or low vision aids.

Generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) is a mental health condition characterized by excessive and persistent worry about multiple events or situations, even when there is no real reason for concern. People with GAD often have difficulty controlling their worries and may experience physical symptoms such as restlessness, fatigue, and muscle tension.
GAD can significantly impact a person's daily life, causing issues with work or school performance, relationships, and overall quality of life. Treatment options for GAD include therapy, medication, or a combination of both. It is important to seek help if you suspect you may have GAD, as it can be effectively managed with the right treatment approach.

Marfan Syndrome is a connective tissue disorder that affects the heart and blood vessels. It is characterized by tall stature, elongated extremities, and a predisposition to aortic dilatation, aortic dissection, and subluxation of the lens.
Malaria caused by the parasite Plasmodium malariae is known as Plasmodium malariae malaria or quartan malaria. It is characterized by recurrent episodes of fever, which occur at 72-hour intervals.

Mixed malaria is a type of malaria that involves infection with more than one species of Plasmodium at the same time. It is also known as malaria fever by more than one parasite or malaria by more than one parasite.

Parkinson's disease is a type of synucleinopathy, which refers to a group of neurological disorders characterized by the accumulation of misfolded alpha-synuclein proteins in neurons. Parkinson's disease specifically has its material basis in degeneration of the central nervous system that often impairs motor skills, speech, and other functions. The exact synonym for Parkinson's disease is "Parkinson disease," and it also goes by the name "paralysis agitans."

postencephalitic parkinson disease is a type of secondary parkinson disease.
postencephalitic parkinson disease has exact synonym postencephalitic parkinsonism.

Estrogen excess is a condition in which a woman has higher levels of estrogen hormone than normal. This can cause various symptoms and health problems, including breast tenderness or soreness, fluid retention, weight gain, and mood changes. It's important to have this condition properly diagnosed and treated by a healthcare professional.

Suppurative thyroiditis, also known as infectious thyroiditis or acute suppurative thyroiditis, is a type of inflammation that occurs in the thyroid gland. It is caused by bacterial infection and can lead to the formation of pus-like material within the gland. Symptoms may include swelling, pain, fever, and difficulty swallowing. Treatment typically involves antibiotics to address the underlying infection and supportive care to manage symptoms.

Riedel's fibrosing thyroiditis is a type of thyroid inflammation characterized by the formation of fibrous tissue around the thyroid gland. It is also known as Riedel's thyroiditis or RFT. It is an uncommon condition that affects the thyroid gland and can cause it to become firm and hard, making it difficult for the gland to function properly. Symptoms may include swelling or enlargement of the thyroid gland, pain in the neck, hoarseness, difficulty swallowing, and a feeling of fullness in the neck. Treatment typically involves medications such as corticosteroids to reduce inflammation and suppress the immune system, and surgery may be necessary if the fibrous tissue becomes too dense or causes significant problems.

systemic primary carnitine deficiency disease is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder that occurs when the body does not have enough carnitine. Carnitine is an essential nutrient that is necessary for the proper functioning of the body's cells and tissues. It helps to convert fat into energy, which is used by the body for various functions such as muscle movement, growth, reproduction, and overall cellular health.
When there is a deficiency of carnitine, the body cannot effectively convert fats into energy, leading to symptoms such as weakness, fatigue, poor muscle function, and decreased physical activity. This condition can be inherited or acquired and can affect various organs and tissues in the body. It is important for individuals with systemic primary carnitine deficiency disease to work with their healthcare provider to manage their symptoms and ensure they receive adequate nutrition and medical care.

Norwegian scabies, also known as crusted scabies, is a type of scabies that occurs in immunocompromised individuals and the elderly. It is characterized by the formation of thick crusts over the skin, accompanied by abundant mites and little to no itching. This form of scabies can be more challenging to treat due to the high number of mites present on the skin.

Parietal lobe neoplasm is a type of brain cancer that occurs in the parietal lobe, which is one of the four lobes of the cerebrum. The parietal lobe is located towards the top and back of the brain, and is responsible for processing sensory information such as touch and temperature. Parietal lobe neoplasm can be classified as either benign or malignant, with malignant tumors being more serious and potentially life-threatening. The diagnosis and treatment of parietal lobe neoplasm depend on the specific type of cancer, as well as the location, size, and extent of the tumor. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to remove the tumor, while in others radiation therapy or chemotherapy may be more appropriate. It is important for individuals with parietal lobe neoplasm to receive proper medical care and follow their doctor's advice closely.

Pyuria is a condition characterized by the presence of pus cells in the urine. It may indicate an infection or inflammation in the urinary tract, and should be evaluated by a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Thrombophlebitis migrans is a condition characterized by the recurrence of thrombosis in various locations. It is also referred to as "traveler's thrombophlebitis." Symptoms may include swelling, pain, and tenderness in the affected veins. Treatment typically involves anticoagulant medications, such as heparin or warfarin, to prevent further clotting.

Protozoal dysentery is a type of dysentery caused by infection with protozoan parasites. It can cause symptoms such as diarrhea, abdominal pain, and blood in the stool. The treatment for protozoal dysentery usually involves antiparasitic medications to kill the parasites causing the infection. Proper hygiene and sanitation are also essential in preventing the spread of this type of dysentery.

Machado-Joseph disease (MJD) is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia, characterized by slow degeneration of the hindbrain. It is caused by an expansion of CAG triplet repeats in the ATXN3 gene. MJD has also been referred to as Azorean disease, SCA3, spinocerebellar ataxia 3 (SCA3), and MESH:D017827.

Capillary leak syndrome (CLS) is a rare disorder characterized by symptoms such as hypotension, hypoalbuminemia, and hemoconcentration due to the leakage of fluid and proteins from damaged capillaries into the surrounding tissues. It can be caused by various factors including autoimmune diseases, infections, or malignancies, among others. The exact cause may not always be determined, and treatment options depend on the underlying cause.

Autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia (ADCA) is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It refers to a group of neurological disorders that affect the cerebellum, which is part of the brain responsible for coordination and balance. ADCA can lead to a range of symptoms, including poor coordination, balance problems, and difficulty with fine motor skills.

Autosomal dominant inheritance means that if one parent has the gene for ADCA, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit the gene and develop the disease. This type of inheritance pattern can increase the likelihood of developing the condition within families, as opposed to recessive or X-linked inheritance patterns.

There are different forms of ADCA, which can be classified based on the underlying genetic mutations that cause them. Some common subtypes include spinocerebellar ataxia type 1 (SCA1), cerebellar ataxia with polyglucosan bodies (CPGB), and dentatorubral-pallidoluysian atrophy (DRPLA).

It's important to note that while there is a genetic component to ADCA, it is not solely determined by genetics. Other factors can contribute to the development of the disease, such as aging and environmental influences.

labyrinthine bilateral dysfunction is a type of labyrinthine dysfunction.
labyrinthine bilateral dysfunction has exact synonym Dysfunction of labyrinthine, bilateral.

Legg-Calve-Perthes disease is a type of osteochondrosis that occurs in children and adolescents. It causes the head of the femur to lose blood supply, leading to death and subsequent fracture of the hip joint. Other terms used to describe this condition include Coxa plana, Juvenile osteochond-hip/pelvis, juvenile osteochondrosis of hip and/or pelvis, Perthe's disease, Perthes disease, pseudocoxalgia, and Legg-Calve-Perthes symptom.

Dracunculiasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease. It involves the parasitic infection by the larvae of the nematode Dracunculus medinensis, which are transmitted to humans through drinking water containing copepods infected with the larvae. The female Dracunculus worm burrows into deeper connective tissues or adjacent to long bones or joints of the extremities and emerges as a whitish filament in the center of a painful ulcer, accompanied by inflammation and secondary bacterial infection. Another name for this condition is Dracontiasis, and it can also be referred to as Infection by Dracunculus medinensis.

Dipetalonemiasis is a type of filariasis, which is caused by the nematode of the genus Dipetalonema. It is transmitted to humans through the bites of mosquitoes that have fed on infected mammals such as porcupines and beavers. The adult worms live subcutaneously or in body cavities, or in the eyes of humans. Symptoms may include necrosis, followed by a granulomatous reaction and fibrosis. It is also known as Infection by Dipetalonema or dipetalonema infectious disease.

Abnormal glucagon secretion, also known as hyperglucagonemia or glucagon excess, occurs when the pancreas produces too much glucagon. This hormone is responsible for raising blood sugar levels and can cause issues if produced in large amounts. Symptoms of abnormal glucagon secretion may include nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, rapid heartbeat, sweating, tremors, and even seizures in severe cases. If left untreated, it can lead to dangerous complications such as diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) or hypoglycemia. It is important to consult a medical professional if you suspect you have abnormal glucagon secretion, as they will be able to diagnose and treat the condition appropriately.

Cerebral degeneration, also known as neurodegenerative disease or brain atrophy, refers to a group of disorders that affect the structure and functioning of the brain over time. It is characterized by the progressive loss of brain cells and tissue, leading to a decrease in cognitive functions such as memory, reasoning, and problem-solving. There are several types of cerebral degeneration, including Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, and multiple sclerosis, among others. These diseases can cause a range of symptoms, from mild cognitive impairment to more severe memory loss and physical disability.

Chronic tubotympanic suppurative otitis media is a type of suppurative otitis media that is characterized by persistent perforation within the pars tensa of the tympanic membrane, intermittent profuse muco-purulent otorrhea, and gradually progressive conductive hearing loss lasting more than 12 weeks. It is caused by recurring upper respiratory infections.
Yes, Cholinergic Urticaria is a type of physical urticaria that occurs as a result of sweating. The exact definition you provided is "Physical urticaria induced by sweating."

Sclerosing keratitis is a type of deep keratitis characterized by inflammation of the anterior sclera and subsequent inflammation of the adjacent cornea with opacification of the corneal stroma. It has symptoms such as pain, red eyes, photophobia, tearing, and blurry vision. Sclerosing keratitis is caused by severe anterior scleritis which can be caused by autoimmune diseases, connective tissue diseases, and infection. The term "sclerosing keratitis" has the same meaning as "Sclerokeratitis".
chronic closed angle glaucoma is a type of primary angle closure glaucoma.

Gonadal dysgenesis is a condition that occurs when an embryo's gonads (ovaries or testes) do not develop properly. This can result in a loss of germ cells, which are responsible for the development of eggs or sperm. The specific cause of gonadal dysgenesis can vary, but it is typically genetic and occurs during fetal development. It is important to note that this condition does not affect an individual's ability to bear children or have a healthy pregnancy if detected early and treated properly.

46 XY gonadal dysgenesis, also known as 46 XY sex reversal or Swyer syndrome, is a genetic condition in which an individual with typically male (XY) chromosomes develops ovarian tissue instead of testicular tissue. This can result in the development of female reproductive organs and secondary sex characteristics. 46 XY gonadal dysgenesis occurs when there is a failure in the development of the testes during fetal development, which leads to a lack of sperm-producing cells (gonocytes) in the affected individual. This condition can be diagnosed through genetic testing and can be managed with hormone replacement therapy.

mixed gonadal dysgenesis is a condition that affects the development of an individual's gonads. It occurs when there is a combination of both testicular and ovarian cells in the affected gonad. This can result in the gonad not developing properly, leading to underdeveloped or absent reproductive organs. Mixed gonadal dysgenesis is a type of gonadal dysgenesis, which is a broader term that refers to any condition that affects the development of an individual's gonads.
